\par HIT POINTS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 When your hit point total reaches 0, you\rquote re disabled. When it reaches \endash 1, you\rquote re dying. When it gets to \endash 10, you\rquote re dead.
\par }{\cf0 
\par SPEED
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Your speed tells you how far you can move in a round and still do something, such as attack or cast a spell. Your speed depends mostly on your race and what armor you\rquote re wearing.
\par Dwarves, gnomes, and halflings have a speed of 20 feet (4 squares), or 15 feet (3 squares) when wearing medium or heavy armor (except for dwarves, who move 20 feet in any armor).
\par Humans, elves, half-elves, and half-orcs have a speed of 30 feet (6 squares), or 20 feet (4 squares) in medium or heavy armor.
\par If you use two move actions in a round (sometimes called a \'93double move\'94 action), you can move up to double your speed. If you spend the entire round to run all out, you can move up to quadruple your speed (or triple if you are in heavy armor).

\par }{\cf0 
\par SAVING THROWS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Generally, when you are subject to an unusual or magical attack, you get a saving throw to avoid or reduce the eff
ect. Like an attack roll, a saving throw is a d20 roll plus a bonus based on your class, level, and an ability score. Your saving throw modifier is: Base save bonus + ability modifier 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Saving Throw Types:}{\fs20\cf0  The three different kinds of saving throws are Fortitude, Reflex, and Will:
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Fortitude: }{\fs20\cf0 These saves measure your ability to stand up to physical punishment or attacks against your vitality and health. Apply your Constitution modifier to your Fortitude saving throws. 
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Reflex: }{\fs20\cf0 These saves test your ability to dodge area attacks. Apply your Dexterity modifier to your Reflex saving throws. 
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Will: }{\fs20\cf0 These saves reflect your resistance to mental influence as well as many magical effects. Apply your Wisdom modifier to your Will saving throws.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Saving Throw Difficulty Class:}{\fs20\cf0  The DC for a save is determined by the attack itself.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Automatic Failures and Successes:}{\fs20\cf0  A natural 1 (the d20 comes up 1) on a saving throw is always a failure (and may cause damage to exposed items
; see Items Surviving after a Saving Throw). A natural 20 (the d20 comes up 20) is always a success.
\par }{\fs36\cf0 
\par INITIATIVE
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Initiative Checks:}{\fs20\cf0  At the start of a battle, each combatant makes an initiative check. An initiative check is a Dexterity check. Each character
 applies his or her Dexterity modifier to the roll. Characters act in order, counting down from highest result to lowest. In every round that follows, the characters act in the same order (unless a character takes an action that results in his or her init
iative changing; see Special Initiative Actions).
\par If two or more combatants have the same initiative check result, the combatants who are tied act in order of total initiative modifier (highest first). If there is still a tie, the tied characters should rol
l again to determine which one of them goes before the other.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Flat-Footed:}{\fs20\cf0  At the start of a battle, before you have had a chance to act (specifically, before your first regular turn in the initiative order), you are flat-footed. You can\rquote t use your Dexteri
ty bonus to AC (if any) while flat-footed. Barbarians and rogues have the uncanny dodge extraordinary ability, which allows them to avoid losing their Dexterity bonus to AC due to being flat-footed.
\par A flat-footed character can\rquote t make attacks of opportunity.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Inaction:}{\fs20\cf0  Even if you can\rquote t take actions, you retain your initiative score for the duration of the encounter.
\par }{\cf0 
\par SURPRISE
\par }{\fs20\cf0 When a combat starts, if you are not aware of your opponents and they are aware of you, you\rquote re surprised.
\par 
\par Determining Awareness
\par Sometimes all the combatants on a side are aware of their opponents, sometimes none are, and sometimes only some of them are. Sometimes a few combatants on each side are aware and the other combatants on each side are unaware.
\par Determining awareness may call for Listen checks, Spot checks, or other checks.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 The Surprise Round:}{\fs20\cf0  If some but not all of the combatants are aware of their opponents, a surprise round happens before regular rounds begin. Any combatants aware of the opponents can act in the surprise round,
 so they roll for initiative. In initiative order (highest to lowest), combatants who started the battle aware of their opponents each take a standard action during the surprise round. You can also take free actions during the surprise round. If no one or
 everyone is surprised, no surprise round occurs.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Unaware Combatants:}{\fs20\cf0  Combatants who are unaware at the start of battle don\rquote t get to act in the surprise round. Unaware combatants are flat-footed because they have not acted yet, so they lose any Dexterity bonus to AC.

