\par ACTIONS IN COMBAT
\par }{\fs20\cf0 
\par }{\cf0 THE COMBAT ROUND
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Each round represents 6 seconds in the game world. A round presents an opportunity for each character involved in a combat situation to take an action. 
\par Each round\rquote s activity begins with the character with the highest initiative result and then proceeds, in order, from there. Each round of a combat uses the same initiative order. When a character\rquote 
s turn comes up in the initiative sequence, that character performs his entire round\rquote s worth of actions. (For exceptions, see Attacks of Opportunity and Special Initiative Actions.)
\par For
 almost all purposes, there is no relevance to the end of a round or the beginning of a round. A round can be a segment of game time starting with the first character to act and ending with the last, but it usually means a span of time from one round to t
he same initiative count in the next round. Effects that last a certain number of rounds end just before the same initiative count that they began on.
\par }{\cf0 
\par ACTION TYPES
\par }{\fs20\cf0 An action\rquote s type essentially tells you how long the action takes to perform (within the fram
ework of the 6-second combat round) and how movement is treated. There are four types of actions: standard actions, move actions, full-round actions, and free actions.
\par In a normal round, you can perform a standard action and a move action, or you can perform a full-round action. You can also perform one or more free actions. You can always take a move action in place of a standard action.
\par In some situations (such as in a surprise round), you may be limited to taking only a single move action or standard action.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Standard Action:}{\fs20\cf0  A standard action allows you to do something, most commonly make an attack or cast a spell. See Table: Actions in Combat for other standard actions.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Move Action:}{\fs20\cf0  A move action allows you to move your speed or perform an action that takes a similar amount of time. See Table: Actions in Combat.
\par You can take a move action in place of a standard action. If you move no actual distance in a round (commonly because you have swapped your move for one or more equivalent actions), you can take one 5-foot step either before, during, or after the action.

\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Full-Round Action:}{\fs20\cf0  A full-round action consumes all your effort during a round. The only movement you can take during a full-round action is a 5-foot step before, during, or after the action. You c
an also perform free actions (see below).
\par Some full-round actions do not allow you to take a 5-foot step.
\par Some full-round actions can be taken as standard actions, but only in situations when you are limited to performing only a standard action during your round. The descriptions of specific actions, below, detail which actions allow this option.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Free Action:}{\fs20\cf0  Free actions consume a very small amount of time and effort. You can perform one or more free actions while taking another action normally. However, there are reasonable limits on what you can really do for free.

\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Not an Action:}{\fs20\cf0  Some activities are so minor that they are not even considered free actions. They literally don\rquote t take any time at all to do and are considered an inherent part of doing something else.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Restricted Activity:}{\fs20\cf0  In some situations, you may be unable to take a full round\rquote 
s worth of actions. In such cases, you are restricted to taking only a single standard action or a single move action (plus free actions as normal). You can\rquote t ta
ke a full-round action (though you can start or complete a full-round action by using a standard action; see below).
