\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Making an attack is a standard action.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Melee Attacks: }{\fs20\cf0 
With a normal melee weapon, you can strike any opponent within 5 feet. (Opponents within 5 feet are considered adjacent to you.) Some melee weapons have reach, as indicated in their descriptions. With a typical reach weapon, you can strike opponents 10 fe
et away, but you can\rquote t strike adjacent foes (those within 5 feet).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Unarmed Attacks:}{\fs20\cf0  Striking for damage with punches, kicks, and head butts is much like attacking with a melee weapon, except for the following:
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Attacks of Opportunity: }{\fs20\cf0 Attacking unarmed provo
kes an attack of opportunity from the character you attack, provided she is armed. The attack of opportunity comes before your attack. An unarmed attack does not provoke attacks of opportunity from other foes nor does it provoke an attack of opportunity f
rom an unarmed foe.
\par An unarmed character can\rquote t take attacks of opportunity (but see \'93Armed\'94 Unarmed Attacks, below).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 \'93Armed\'94 Unarmed Attacks: }{\fs20\cf0 Sometimes a character\rquote s or creature\rquote s unarmed attack counts as an armed attack. A monk, a character with the Improv
ed Unarmed Strike feat, a spellcaster delivering a touch attack spell, and a creature with natural physical weapons all count as being armed.
\par Note that being armed counts for both offense and defense (the character can make attacks of opportunity)
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Unarmed Strike Damage: }{\fs20\cf0 An unarmed strike from a Medium character deals 1d3 points of damage (plus your Strength modifier, as normal). A Small character\rquote s unarmed strike deals 1d2 points of damage, while a Large character
\rquote s unarmed strike deals 1d4 points of damage. All damage from unarmed strikes is nonlethal damage. Unarmed strikes count as light weapons (for purposes of two-weapon attack penalties and so on).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Dealing Lethal Damage: }{\fs20\cf0 You can specify that your unarmed strike will deal lethal damage before you make your attack roll, but you take a \endash 
4 penalty on your attack roll. If you have the Improved Unarmed Strike feat, you can deal lethal damage with an unarmed strike without taking a penalty on the attack roll.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Ranged Attacks:}{\fs20\cf0  With a ranged weapon, you can shoot or throw at any target that is within the weapon\rquote 
s maximum range and in line of sight. The maximum range for a thrown weapon is five range increments. For projectile weapons, it is ten range increments. Some ranged weapons have shorter maximum ranges, as specified in their descriptions.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Attack Rolls:}{\fs20\cf0  An attack roll represents your attempts to strike your opponent. 
\par Your attack roll is 1d20 + your attack bonus with the weapon you\rquote re using. If the result is at least as high as the target\rquote s AC, you hit and deal damage.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Automatic Misses and Hits:}{\fs20\cf0  A natural 1 (the d20 comes up 1) on the attack roll is always a miss. A natural 20 (the d20 comes up 20) is always a hit. A natural 20 is also a threat\emdash a possible critical hit.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Damage Rolls:}{\fs20\cf0  If the attack roll result equals or exceeds the target\rquote s AC, the attack hits and you deal damage. Roll the appropriate damage for your weapon. Damage is deducted from the target\rquote s current hit points.

\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Multiple Attacks:}{\fs20\cf0  A character who can make more than one attack per round must use the full attack action (see Full-Round Actions, below) in order to get more than one attack.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Shooting or Throwing into a Melee:}{\fs20\cf0  If you shoot or throw a ranged weapon at a target engaged in melee with a friendly character, you take a \endash 4 penalty on your atta
ck roll. Two characters are engaged in melee if they are enemies of each other and either threatens the other. (An unconscious or otherwise immobilized character is not considered engaged unless he is actually being attacked.)
\par If your target (or the part of your target you\rquote re aiming at, if it\rquote s a big target) is at least 10 feet away from the nearest friendly character, you can avoid the \endash 4 penalty, even if the creature you\rquote 
re aiming at is engaged in melee with a friendly character.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Precise Shot: }{\fs20\cf0 If you have the Precise Shot feat you don\rquote t take this penalty.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Fighting Defensively as a Standard Action:}{\fs20\cf0  You can choose to fight defensively when attacking. If you do so, you take a \endash 4 penalty on all attacks in a round to gain a +2 dodge bonus to AC for the same round.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Critical Hits:}{\fs20\cf0  When you make an attack roll and get a natural 20 (the d20 shows 20), you hit regardless of your target\rquote s Armor Class, and you have scored a threat. The hit might be a critical hit (or \'93crit\'94
). To find out if it\rquote s a critical hit, you immediately make a critical roll\emdash another attack roll with all the same modifiers as the attack roll you just made. If the critical roll also results in a hit against the target\rquote 
s AC, your original hit is a critical hit. (The critical roll just needs to hit to give you a crit. It doesn\rquote t need to come up 20 again.) If the critical roll is a miss, then your hit is just a regular hit.
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 A critical hit means that you roll your damage more than once, with all your usual bonuses, and add th
e rolls together. Unless otherwise specified, the threat range for a critical hit on an attack roll is 20, and the multiplier is x2.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i\fs20\cf0 Exception:}{\b\fs20\cf0  }{\fs20\cf0 Extra damage over and above a weapon\rquote 
s normal damage is not multiplied when you score a critical hit.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Increased Threat Range:}{\b\fs20\cf0  }{\fs20\cf0 Sometimes your threat range is greater than 20. That is, you can score a threat on a lower number. In such cases, a roll of lower than 20 is not an automatic hit. Any attack roll that doesn
\rquote t result in a hit is not a threat.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Increased Critical Multiplier:}{\b\fs20\cf0  }{\fs20\cf0 Some weapons deal better than double damage on a critical hit.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Spells and Critical Hits: }{\fs20\cf0 A spell that requires an attack roll}{\i\fs20\cf0  }{\fs20\cf0 can score a critical hit. A spell attack that requires no attack roll}{\i\fs20\cf0  }{\fs20\cf0 cannot score a critical hit.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Cast a Spell
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Most spells require 1 standard action to cast. You can cast such a spell either before or after you take a move action. 

\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Note: }{\fs20\cf0 You retain your Dexterity bonus to AC while casting.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Spell Components:}{\fs20\cf0  To cast a spell with a verbal (V) component, your character must speak in a firm voice. If you\rquote re gagged or in the area of a }{\i\fs20\cf0 silence }{\fs20\cf0 spell, you can\rquote 
t cast such a spell. A spellcaster who has been deafened has a 20% chance to spoil any spell he tries to cast if that spell has a verbal component.
\par To cast a spell with a somatic (S) component, you must gesture freely with at least one hand. You can\rquote t cast a spell of this type while bound, grappling, or with both your hands full or occupied.
\par To cast a spell with a material (M), focus (F), or divine focus (DF) component, you have to have the proper materials, as described by the spell. Unless these materials are elaborate}{\i\fs20\cf0  }{\fs20\cf0 
preparing these materials is a free action. For material components and focuses whose costs are not listed, you can assume that you have them if you have your spell component pouch.
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 
Some spells have an experience point (XP) component and entail an experience point cost to you. No spell can restore the lost XP. You cannot spend so much XP that you lose a level, so you cannot cast the spell unless you have
 enough XP to spare. However, you may, on gaining enough XP to achieve a new level, immediately spend the XP on casting the spell rather than keeping it to advance a level. The XP are expended when you cast the spell, whether or not the casting succeeds.

\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\fs20\cf0 Concentration:}{\fs20\cf0  You must concentrate to cast a spell. If you can\rquote t concentrate you can\rquote 
t cast a spell. If you start casting a spell but something interferes with your concentration you must make a Concentration check or lose the spell. The check\rquote s DC depends
 on what is threatening your concentration (see the Concentration skill). If you fail, the spell fizzles with no effect. If you prepare spells, it is lost from preparation. If you cast at will, it counts against your daily limit of spells even though you 
did not cast it successfully.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Concentrating to Maintain a Spell:}{\fs20\cf0  Some spells require continued concentration to keep them going. Concentrating to maintain a spell is a standard action that doesn\rquote 
t provoke an attack of opportunity. Anything that could break your concentration when casting a spell can keep you from concentrating to maintain a spell. If your concentration breaks, the spell ends.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Casting Time:}{\fs20\cf0  Most spells have a casting time of 1 standard action. A spell cast in this manner immediately takes effect.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Attacks of Opportunity:}{\fs20\cf0 
 Generally, if you cast a spell, you provoke attacks of opportunity from threatening enemies. If you take damage from an attack of opportunity, you must make a Concentration check (DC 10 + points of damage taken + spell level) o
r lose the spell. Spells that require only a free action to cast don\rquote t provoke attacks of opportunity.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Casting on the Defensive:}{\fs20\cf0  Casting a spell while on the defensive does not provoke an attack of opportunity. It does, however, require a Concentration check (DC 15 + spell level) to pull off. Failure means that you lose the spell.

\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Touch Spells in Combat:}{\fs20\cf0  Many spells have a range of touch. To use these spells, you cast the spell and then touch the subject, either in the same round or any time later. In the s
ame round that you cast the spell, you may also touch (or attempt to touch) the target. You may take your move before casting the spell, after touching the target, or between casting the spell and touching the target. You can automatically touch one frien
d or use the spell on yourself, but to touch an opponent, you must succeed on an attack roll.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Touch Attacks: }{\fs20\cf0 Touching an opponent with a touch spell is considered to be an armed attack and therefore does not provoke attacks of opportunity. However, the act 
of casting a spell does provoke an attack of opportunity. Touch attacks come in two types: melee touch attacks and ranged touch attacks. You can score critical hits with either type of attack. Your opponent\rquote 
s AC against a touch attack does not include any armor bonus, shield bonus, or natural armor bonus. His size modifier, Dexterity modifier, and deflection bonus (if any) all apply normally.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Holding the Charge: }{\fs20\cf0 If you don\rquote t discharge the spell in the round when you cast the spell, you can hold the discharg
e of the spell (hold the charge) indefinitely. You can continue to make touch attacks round after round. You can touch one friend as a standard action or up to six friends as a full-round action. If you touch anything or anyone while holding a charge, eve
n unintentionally, the spell discharges. If you cast another spell, the touch spell dissipates. Alternatively, you may make a normal unarmed attack (or an attack with a natural weapon) while holding a charge. In this case, you aren\rquote 
t considered armed and you provoke attacks of opportunity as normal for the attack. (If your unarmed attack or natural weapon attack doesn\rquote 
t provoke attacks of opportunity, neither does this attack.) If the attack hits, you deal normal damage for your unarmed attack or natural weapon and the spell discharges. If the attack misses, you are still holding the charge.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Dismiss a Spell:}{\fs20\cf0  Dismissing an active spell is a standard action that doesn\rquote t provoke attacks of opportunity.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Activate Magic Item
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Many magic items don\rquote t need to be activ
ated. However, certain magic items need to be activated, especially potions, scrolls, wands, rods, and staffs. Activating a magic item is a standard action (unless the item description indicates otherwise).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Spell Completion Items: }{\fs20\cf0 
Activating a spell completion item is the equivalent of casting a spell. It requires concentration and provokes attacks of opportunity. You lose the spell if your concentration is broken, and you can attempt to activate the item while on the defensive, as
 with casting a spell.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Spell Trigger, Command Word, or Use-Activated Items: }{\fs20\cf0 Activating any of these kinds of items does not require concentration and does not provoke attacks of opportunity.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Use Special Ability
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Using a special ability is usually a standard
 action, but whether it is a standard action, a full-round action, or not an action at all is defined by the ability.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Spell-Like Abilities:}{\fs20\cf0  Using a spell-like ability works like casting a spell in that it requires concentration and provokes attacks of oppo
rtunity. Spell-like abilities can be disrupted. If your concentration is broken, the attempt to use the ability fails, but the attempt counts as if you had used the ability. The casting time of a spell-like ability is 1 standard action, unless the ability
 description notes otherwise.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Using a Spell-Like Ability on the Defensive: }{\fs20\cf0 You may attempt to use a spell-like ability on the defensive, just as with casting a spell. If the Concentration check (DC 15 + spell level) fails, you can\rquote 
t use the ability, but the attempt counts as if you had used the ability.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Supernatural Abilities:}{\fs20\cf0  Using a supernatural ability is usually a standard action (unless defined otherwise by the ability\rquote s description). Its use cannot be disrupted, does not require concentration, and does
 not provoke attacks of opportunity.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Extraordinary Abilities:}{\fs20\cf0  Using an extraordinary ability is usually not an action because most extraordinary abilities automatically happen in a reactive fashion. Those extraordinary abilities that are actions are usuall
y standard actions that cannot be disrupted, do not require concentration, and do not provoke attacks of opportunity.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Total Defense
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 You can defend yourself as a standard action. You get a +4 dodge bonus to your AC for 1 round. Your AC improves at the star
t of this action. You can\rquote t combine total defense with fighting defensively or with the benefit of the Combat Expertise feat (since both of those require you to declare an attack or full attack). You can\rquote 
t make attacks of opportunity while using total defense.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Start/Complete Full-Round Action
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 The \'93start full-round action\'94
 standard action lets you start undertaking a full-round action, which you can complete in the following round by using another standard action. You can\rquote t use this action to start or complete a full attack, charge, run, or withdraw.
\par }{\cf0 
\par MOVE ACTIONS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 With the exception of specific movement-related skills, most move actions don\rquote t require a check.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Move
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 The simplest move action is moving your speed. If you take this kind of move action during your turn, you can\rquote 
t also take a 5-foot step.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 
Many nonstandard modes of movement are covered under this category, including climbing (up to one-quarter of your speed) and swimming (up to one-quarter of your speed).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Accelerated Climbing:}{\fs20\cf0  You can climb one-half your speed as a move action by accepting a \endash 5 penalty on your Climb check.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Crawling:}{\fs20\cf0  You can crawl 5 feet as a move action. Crawling incurs attacks of opportunity from any attackers who threaten you at any point of your crawl.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Draw or Sheathe a Weapon
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Dr
awing a weapon so that you can use it in combat, or putting it away so that you have a free hand, requires a move action. This action also applies to weapon-like objects carried in easy reach, such as wands. If your weapon or weapon-like object is stored 
in a pack or otherwise out of easy reach, treat this action as retrieving a stored item.
\par If you have a base attack bonus of +1 or higher, you may draw a weapon as a free action combined with a regular move. If you have the Two-Weapon Fighting feat, you can 
draw two light or one-handed weapons in the time it would normally take you to draw one.
\par Drawing ammunition for use with a ranged weapon (such as arrows, bolts, sling bullets, or shuriken) is a free action.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Ready or Loose a Shield
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 
Strapping a shield to your arm to gain its shield bonus to your AC, or unstrapping and dropping a shield so you can use your shield hand for another purpose, requires a move action. If you have a base attack bonus of +1 or higher, you can ready or loose a
 shield as a free action combined with a regular move.
\par Dropping a carried (but not worn) shield is a free action.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Manipulate an Item
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 In most cases, moving or manipulating an item is a move action.
\par This includes retrieving or putting away a stored item, picking up an item, moving a heavy object, and opening a door. Examples of this kind of action, along with whether they incur an attack of opportunity, are given in Table: Actions in Combat.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Direct or Redirect a Spell
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Some spells}{\i\fs20\cf0  }{\fs20\cf0 allow you to redirect the ef
fect to new targets or areas after you cast the spell. Redirecting a spell requires a move action and does not provoke attacks of opportunity or require concentration.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Stand Up
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Standing up from a prone position requires a move action and provokes attacks of opportunity.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Mount/Dismount a Steed
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Mounting or dismounting from a steed requires a move action.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Fast Mount or Dismount:}{\fs20\cf0  You can mount or dismount as a free action with a DC 20 Ride check (your armor check penalty, if any, applies to this check). If yo
u fail the check, mounting or dismounting is a move action instead. (You can\rquote t attempt a fast mount or fast dismount unless you can perform the mount or dismount as a move action in the current round.)
\par }{\cf0 
\par FULL-ROUND ACTIONS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 A full-round action requires an entire round to complete. Thus, it can\rquote t be coupled with a standard or a move action, though if it does not involve moving any distance, you can take a 5-foot step.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Full Attack
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 If you get more than one attack per round because your base attack bonus is high
 enough, because you fight with two weapons or a double weapon or for some special reason you must use a full-round action to get your additional attacks. You do not need to specify the targets of your attacks ahead of time. You can see how the earlier at
tacks turn out before assigning the later ones.
\par The only movement you can take during a full attack is a 5-foot step. You may take the step before, after, or between your attacks.
\par If you get multiple attacks because your base attack bonus is high enough, yo
u must make the attacks in order from highest bonus to lowest. If you are using two weapons, you can strike with either weapon first. If you are using a double weapon, you can strike with either part of the weapon first.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Deciding between an Attack or a Full Attack:}{\fs20\cf0  After your first attack, you can decide to take a move action instead of making your remaining attacks, depending on how the first attack turns out. If you\rquote 
ve already taken a 5-foot step, you can\rquote t use your move action to move any distance, but you could still use a different kind of move action.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Fighting Defensively as a Full-Round Action:}{\fs20\cf0  You can choose to fight defensively when taking a full attack action. If you do so, you take a \endash 4 penalty on all attacks in a round to gain a +2 dodge bonus to
 AC for the same round.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Cleave:}{\fs20\cf0  The extra attack granted by the Cleave feat or Great Cleave feat can be taken whenever they apply. This is an exception to the normal limit to the number of attacks you can take when not using a full attack action.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Cast a Spell
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 
A spell that takes 1 round to cast is a full-round action. It comes into effect just before the beginning of your turn in the round after you began casting the spell. You then act normally after the spell is completed.
\par A spell that takes 1 min
ute to cast comes into effect just before your turn 1 minute later (and for each of those 10 rounds, you are casting a spell as a full-round action). These actions must be consecutive and uninterrupted, or the spell automatically fails.
\par When you begin a sp
ell that takes 1 round or longer to cast, you must continue the invocations, gestures, and concentration from one round to just before your turn in the next round (at least). If you lose concentration after starting the spell and before it is complete, yo
u lose the spell.
\par You only provoke attacks of opportunity when you begin casting a spell, even though you might continue casting for at least one full round. While casting a spell, you don\rquote t threaten any squares around you.
\par This action is otherwise identical to the cast a spell action described under Standard Actions.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Casting a Metamagic Spell:}{\fs20\cf0  Sorcerers and bards must take more time to cast a metamagic spell (one enhanced by a metamagic feat) than a regular spell. If a spell\rquote s normal casting time is 1 stand
ard action, casting a metamagic version of the spell is a full-round action for a sorcerer or bard. Note that this isn\rquote t the same as a spell with a 1-round casting time\emdash 
the spell takes effect in the same round that you begin casting, and you aren\rquote t require
d to continue the invocations, gestures, and concentration until your next turn. For spells with a longer casting time, it takes an extra full-round action to cast the metamagic spell.
\par Clerics must take more time to spontaneously cast a metamagic version of a }{\i\fs20\cf0 cure }{\fs20\cf0 or }{\i\fs20\cf0 inflict }{\fs20\cf0 spell.}{\i\fs20\cf0  }{\fs20\cf0 
Spontaneously casting a metamagic version of a spell with a casting time of 1 standard action is a full-round action, and spells with longer casting times take an extra full-round action to cast.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Use Special Ability
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Using a special ability is usually a standard action, but some may be full-round actions, as defined by the ability.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Withdraw
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 
Withdrawing from melee combat is a full-round action. When you withdraw, you can move up to double your speed. The square you start out in is
 not considered threatened by any opponent you can see, and therefore visible enemies do not get attacks of opportunity against you when you move from that square. (Invisible enemies still get attacks of opportunity against you, and you can\rquote 
t withdraw from combat if you\rquote re blinded.) You can\rquote t take a 5-foot step during the same round in which you withdraw.
\par If, during the process of withdrawing, you move out of a threatened square (other than the one you started in), enemies get attacks of opportunity as normal.
\par You may not withdraw using a form of movement for which you don\rquote t have a listed speed. 
\par Note that despite the name of this action, you don\rquote t actually have to leave combat entirely.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Restricted Withdraw:}{\fs20\cf0  If you are limited to taking only a standard action each round you can withdraw as a standard action. In this case, you may move up to your speed (rather than up to double your speed).
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Run
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 You can run as a full-round action. (If you do, you do not also get a 5-foot step.) When you run, you can move up to
 four times your speed in a straight line (or three times your speed if you\rquote re in heavy armor). You lose any Dexterity bonus to AC unless you have the Run feat 
\par You can run for a number of rounds equal to your Constitution score, but after that you must ma
ke a DC 10 Constitution check to continue running. You must check again each round in which you continue to run, and the DC of this check increases by 1 for each check you have made. When you fail this check, you must stop running. A character who has run
 to his limit must rest for 1 minute (10 rounds) before running again. During a rest period, a character can move no faster than a normal move action.
\par You can\rquote t run across difficult terrain or if you can\rquote t see where you\rquote re going.
\par A run represents a speed of about 12 miles per hour for an unencumbered human.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Move 5 Feet through Difficult Terrain
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 In some situations, your movement may be so hampered that you don\rquote 
t have sufficient speed even to move 5 feet (a single square). In such a case, you may spend a full-round action to move 5 feet (1 square) in any direction, even diagonally. Even though this looks like a 5-foot step, it\rquote 
s not, and thus it provokes attacks of opportunity normally.
\par }{\cf0 
\par FREE ACTIONS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Free actions don\rquote t take any time at all, though there may be limits to the number of free actions you can perform in a turn. Free actions rarely incur attacks of opportunity. Some common free actions are described below.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Drop an Item
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Dropping an item in your space or into an adjacent square is a free action.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Drop Prone
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Dropping to a prone position in your space is a free action.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Speak
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 In general, speaking is a free action that you can perform even when it isn\rquote 
t your turn. Speaking more than few sentences is generally beyond the limit of a free action.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Cease Concentration on Spell
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 You can stop concentrating on an active spell as a free action.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Cast a Quickened Spell
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 You can cast a quickened spell (see the Quicken Spell feat) or any spell whose casting time is designated 
as a free action as a free action. Only one such spell can be cast in any round, and such spells don\rquote t count toward your normal limit of one spell per round. Casting a spell with a casting time of a free action doesn\rquote 
t incur an attack of opportunity.
\par }{\cf0 
\par MISCELLANEOUS ACTIONS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Take 5-Foot Step
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 You can move 5 feet in any round when you don\rquote 
t perform any other kind of movement. Taking this 5-foot step never provokes an attack of opportunity. You can\rquote t take more than one 5-foot step in a round, and you can\rquote t take a 5-foot step in the same round when you move any distance.
\par You can take a 5-foot step before, during, or after your other actions in the round. 
\par You can only take a 5-foot-step if your movement isn\rquote t hampered by difficult terrain or darkness. Any creature with a speed of 5 feet or less can\rquote t take a 5-foot step, since moving even 5 feet requires a move action for such a slow creature.

\par You may not take a 5-foot step using a form of movement for which you do not have a listed speed. 
\par }{\cf0 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Use Feat
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Certain feats 
let you take special actions in combat. Other feats do not require actions themselves, but they give you a bonus when attempting something you can already do. Some feats are not meant to be used within the framework of combat. The individual feat descript
ions tell you what you need to know about them.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Use Skill
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 
Most skill uses are standard actions, but some might be move actions, full-round actions, free actions, or something else entirely.
\par The individual skill descriptions tell you what sorts of actions are required to perform skills.
\par }{\fs36\cf0 
\par INJURY AND DEATH
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Your hit points measure how hard you are to kill. No matter how many hit points you lose, your character isn\rquote t hindered in any way until your hit points drop to 0 or lower.
\par }{\cf0 
\par LOSS OF HIT POINTS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 The most common way that your character gets hurt is to take lethal damage and lose hit points
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 What Hit Points Represent:}{\fs20\cf0  Hit points mean two things in the game world: the ability to take physical punishment and keep going, and the ability to turn a serious blow into a less serious one.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Effects of Hit Point Damage:}{\fs20\cf0  Damage doesn\rquote t slow you down until your current hit points reach 0 or lower. At 0 hit points, you\rquote re disabled.
\par At from \endash 1 to \endash 9 hit points, you\rquote re dying.
\par At \endash 10 or lower, you\rquote re dead.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Massive Damage: }{\fs20\cf0 If you ever sustain a single attack deals 50 points of damage or more and it doesn\rquote t kill you outright, you must make a DC 15 Fortitude save. If this saving throw fails, you die regardless of your cu
rrent hit points. If you take 50 points of damage or more from multiple attacks, no one of which dealt 50 or more points of damage itself, the massive damage rule does not apply.
\par }{\cf0 
\par DISABLED (0 HIT POINTS)
\par }{\fs20\cf0 When your current hit points drop to exactly 0, you\rquote re disabled.
\par You can only take a single move or standard action each turn (but not both, nor can you take full-round actions). You can take move actions without further injuring yourself, but if you perform any standard action (or any other strenuous actio
n) you take 1 point of damage after the completing the act. Unless your activity increased your hit points, you are now at \endash 1 hit points, and you\rquote re dying.
\par Healing that raises your hit points above 0 makes you fully functional again, just as if you\rquote d never been reduced to 0 or fewer hit points.
\par You can also become disabled when recovering from dying. In this case, it\rquote s a step toward recovery, and you can have fewer than 0 hit points (see Stable Characters and Recovery, below).
\par }{\cf0 
\par DYING (\endash 1 TO \endash 9 HIT POINTS)
\par }{\fs20\cf0 When your character\rquote s current hit points drop to between \endash 1 and \endash 9 inclusive, he\rquote s dying.
\par A dying character immediately falls unconscious and can take no actions.
\par A dying character loses 1 hit point every round. This continues until the character dies or becomes stable (see below).
\par }{\cf0 
\par DEAD (\endash 10 HIT POINTS OR LOWER)
\par }{\fs20\cf0 When your character\rquote s current hit points drop to \endash 10 or lower, or if he takes massive damage (see above), he\rquote s dead. A character can also die from taking ability damage or suffering an ability drain
 that reduces his Constitution to 0.
\par }{\cf0 
\par STABLE CHARACTERS AND RECOVERY
\par }{\fs20\cf0 On the next turn after a character is reduced to between \endash 1 and \endash 9 hit points and on all subsequent turns, roll d% to see whether the dying character becomes stable. He has a 10% chance of becoming stable. If he doesn\rquote 
t, he loses 1 hit point. (A character who\rquote s unconscious or dying can\rquote t use any special action that changes the initiative count on which his action occurs.)
\par If the character\rquote s hit points drop to \endash 10 or lower, he\rquote s dead.
\par You can keep a dying character from losing any more hit points and make him stable with a DC 15 Heal check.
\par If any sort of healing cures the dying character of even 1 point of damage, he stops losing hit points and becomes stable.
\par Healing that raises the dying character\rquote s hit points to 0 makes him conscious and disabled. Healing that raises his hit points to 1 or more makes him fully functional again, just as if he\rquote 
d never been reduced to 0 or lower. A spellcaster retains the spellcasting capability she had before dropping below 0 hit points.
\par A stable character who has been tended by a healer or who has been magically healed eventually regains
 consciousness and recovers hit points naturally. If the character has no one to tend him, however, his life is still in danger, and he may yet slip away.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Recovering with Help:}{\fs20\cf0  One hour after a tended, dying character becomes stable, roll d%. He has a 10% 
chance of becoming conscious, at which point he is disabled (as if he had 0 hit points). If he remains unconscious, he has the same chance to revive and become disabled every hour. Even if unconscious, he recovers hit points naturally. He is back to norma
l when his hit points rise to 1 or higher.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Recovering without Help:}{\fs20\cf0  A severely wounded character left alone usually dies. He has a small chance, however, of recovering on his own. 
\par A character who becomes stable on his own (by making the 10% roll while dyin
g) and who has no one to tend to him still loses hit points, just at a slower rate. He has a 10% chance each hour of becoming conscious. Each time he misses his hourly roll to become conscious, he loses 1 hit point. He also does not recover hit points thr
ough natural healing.
\par Even once he becomes conscious and is disabled, an unaided character still does not recover hit points naturally. Instead, each day he has a 10% chance to start recovering hit points naturally (starting with that day); otherwise, he loses 1 hit point.

\par Once an unaided character starts recovering hit points naturally, he is no longer in danger of naturally losing hit points (even if his current hit point total is negative).
\par }{\cf0 
\par HEALING
\par }{\fs20\cf0 After taking damage, you can recover hit points through natural healing or through magical healing. In any case, you can\rquote t regain hit points past your full normal hit point total.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Natural Healing:}{\fs20\cf0  With a full night\rquote s rest (8 hours of sleep or more), you recover 1 hit point per character level. Any significant interruption during your rest prevents you from healing that night.
\par If you undergo complete bed rest for an entire day and night, you recover twice your character level in hit points. 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Magical Healing:}{\fs20\cf0  Various abilities and spells can restore hit points.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Healing Limits:}{\fs20\cf0  You can never recover more hit points than you lost. Magical healing won\rquote t raise your current hit points higher than your full normal hit point total.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Healing Ability Damage:}{\fs20\cf0  Ability damage is temporary, just as hit point damage is. Ability d
amage returns at the rate of 1 point per night of rest (8 hours) for each affected ability score. Complete bed rest restores 2 points per day (24 hours) for each affected ability score.
