 Certain attacks deal nonlethal damage. Other effects, such as heat or being exhausted, also deal nonlethal damage. When you take nonlethal damage, keep a running total of how much you\rquote ve accumulated. }{\i\fs20\cf0 
Do not deduct the nonlethal damage number from your current hit points. }{\fs20\cf0 It is not \'93real\'94 damage. Instead, when your nonlethal damage equals your current hit points, you\rquote 
re staggered, and when it exceeds your current hit points, you fall unconscious. It doesn\rquote 
t matter whether the nonlethal damage equals or exceeds your current hit points because the nonlethal damage has gone up or because your current hit points have gone down.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Nonlethal Damage with a Weapon that Deals Lethal Damage: }{\fs20\cf0 You can use a melee weapon that deals lethal damage to deal nonlethal damage instead, but you take a \endash 4 penalty on your attack roll.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Lethal Damage with a Weapon that Deals Nonlethal Damage: }{\fs20\cf0 You can use a weapon that deals nonlethal damage, including an unarmed strike, to deal lethal damage instead, but you take a \endash 4 penalty on your attack roll.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Staggered and Unconscious:}{\fs20\cf0  When your nonlethal damage equals your current hit points, you\rquote re staggered. You can only take a standard action or a move action in each round. Y
ou cease being staggered when your current hit points once again exceed your nonlethal damage.
\par When your nonlethal damage exceeds your current hit points, you fall unconscious. While unconscious, you are helpless.
\par Spellcasters who fall unconscious retain any spellcasting ability they had before going unconscious.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Healing Nonlethal Damage:}{\fs20\cf0  You heal nonlethal damage at the rate of 1 hit point per hour per character level.
\par When a spell or a magical power cures hit point damage, it also removes an equal amount of nonlethal damage.}{\fs36\cf0 
